<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="46" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1458,1734]" pageId="1" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,1458,1483]" pageId="1" pageNumber="46">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[280,373,1459,1483]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Drusilla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[280,373,1459,1483]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="46">Drusilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from all other Nearctic genera belonging to the tribe 
<taxonomicName box="[1213,1359,1458,1482]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Lomechusini">Lomechusini</taxonomicName>
by the following combination of characters: 
<number box="[570,582,1494,1518]" pageId="1" pageNumber="46" value="1.0">1</number>
) head with distinct neck (
<figureCitation box="[872,980,1494,1518]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 3" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1962,1985]" captionTargetBox="[174,1413,772,1939]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[174,1413,772,1941]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 3. Holotypes of Drusilla. Dorsal habitus: 1) D. nearctica; 2) D. ashei. 3) D. nearctica lateral view of head and thorax." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/210859/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="46">
Figs. 
<number box="[935,980,1494,1518]" pageId="1" pageNumber="46" value="2.0" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="1.0">1–3</number>
</figureCitation>
); 
<number box="[1001,1016,1494,1518]" pageId="1" pageNumber="46" value="2.0">2</number>
) head with occipital suture extremely short, terminating proximal to gena (
<figureCitation box="[562,629,1530,1554]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 3" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1962,1985]" captionTargetBox="[174,1413,772,1939]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[174,1413,772,1941]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 3. Holotypes of Drusilla. Dorsal habitus: 1) D. nearctica; 2) D. ashei. 3) D. nearctica lateral view of head and thorax." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/210859/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="46">
Fig. 
<number box="[614,629,1530,1554]" pageId="1" pageNumber="46" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
); 
<number box="[652,666,1530,1554]" pageId="1" pageNumber="46" value="3.0">3</number>
) in lateral view, vertex sloping rapidly posteriorly to form a vertical, sometimes almost deflexed profile (
<figureCitation box="[580,654,1566,1590]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 3" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1962,1985]" captionTargetBox="[174,1413,772,1939]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[174,1413,772,1941]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 3. Holotypes of Drusilla. Dorsal habitus: 1) D. nearctica; 2) D. ashei. 3) D. nearctica lateral view of head and thorax." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/210859/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="46">
Fig. 
<number box="[639,654,1566,1590]" pageId="1" pageNumber="46" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
); 
<number box="[684,699,1566,1590]" pageId="1" pageNumber="46" value="4.0">4</number>
) maxillary components, especially galea, elongate, forming a protruding complex visible past labrum in dorsal view (
<figureCitation box="[771,847,1602,1626]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 3" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1962,1985]" captionTargetBox="[174,1413,772,1939]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[174,1413,772,1941]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 3. Holotypes of Drusilla. Dorsal habitus: 1) D. nearctica; 2) D. ashei. 3) D. nearctica lateral view of head and thorax." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/210859/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="46">Figs. 1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[861,877,1602,1626]" captionStart="FIGURES 4 – 5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1934,1957]" captionTargetBox="[197,1388,858,1905]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[185,1402,844,1913]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 4 – 5. Mouthparts of Drusilla nearctica. 4) prementum, ventral; 5) right maxilla, ventral. Scale bars (0.1 mm): I = 5; II = 4." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/210860/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="46">5</figureCitation>
); 
<number box="[899,913,1602,1626]" pageId="1" pageNumber="46" value="5.0">5</number>
) labial palpomeres subequal in length (
<figureCitation box="[1353,1422,1602,1626]" captionStart="FIGURES 4 – 5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1934,1957]" captionTargetBox="[197,1388,858,1905]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[185,1402,844,1913]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 4 – 5. Mouthparts of Drusilla nearctica. 4) prementum, ventral; 5) right maxilla, ventral. Scale bars (0.1 mm): I = 5; II = 4." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/210860/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="46">
Fig. 
<number box="[1405,1422,1602,1626]" pageId="1" pageNumber="46" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
); ultimate labial palpomere slightly curved inwards (
<figureCitation box="[769,846,1638,1662]" captionStart="FIGURES 4 – 5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1934,1957]" captionTargetBox="[197,1388,858,1905]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[185,1402,844,1913]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 4 – 5. Mouthparts of Drusilla nearctica. 4) prementum, ventral; 5) right maxilla, ventral. Scale bars (0.1 mm): I = 5; II = 4." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/210860/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="46">
Fig. 
<number box="[829,846,1638,1662]" pageId="1" pageNumber="46" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
); 
<number box="[875,889,1638,1662]" pageId="1" pageNumber="46" value="6.0">6</number>
) glossa relatively long, bifid with prominent separation (
<figureCitation box="[284,356,1674,1698]" captionStart="FIGURES 4 – 5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1934,1957]" captionTargetBox="[197,1388,858,1905]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[185,1402,844,1913]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 4 – 5. Mouthparts of Drusilla nearctica. 4) prementum, ventral; 5) right maxilla, ventral. Scale bars (0.1 mm): I = 5; II = 4." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/210860/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="46">
Fig. 
<number box="[339,356,1674,1698]" pageId="1" pageNumber="46" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
); 
<number box="[380,395,1674,1698]" pageId="1" pageNumber="46" value="7.0">7</number>
) dorsal abdominal surface sub-glabrous, with a few scattered setae (including macrosetae, 
<figureCitation box="[151,258,1710,1734]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 3" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1962,1985]" captionTargetBox="[174,1413,772,1939]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[174,1413,772,1941]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 3. Holotypes of Drusilla. Dorsal habitus: 1) D. nearctica; 2) D. ashei. 3) D. nearctica lateral view of head and thorax." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/210859/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="46">
Figs. 
<number box="[213,258,1710,1734]" pageId="1" pageNumber="46" value="1.5" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="1.0">1–2</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
